an rgmdl (Rat Game MoDeL) file holds specifications tying models
and textures together into a cohesive object for the game. it
consists of a series of statements that load files and modify
loaded assets. 
MODEL STATEMENTS
- model = ...;
  loads the model at the filepath ..., relative to
	assets/model/. currently you can only have one model per file.
  the whitespace before and after the = is optional, leading
  whitespace is trimmed (but trailing until the ; is not)
- model_scale(x,y,z),model_offset(x,y,z) and model_rotate(x,y,z)
  applies a transformation along each axis. the units of
	rotation are in fractions of a whole rotation. everything is
	floating-point so you can use like 1e-1 for 0.1 (probably)
TEXTURE STATEMENTS
- texture = ...;
	loads the texture at the filepath ..., relative to
  assets/texture/. you can have as many textures as you want per
  file and they're added to a list with indices starting at 0 in
  order of where in the file they are. whitespace is trimmed in
  the same way as with models.
- texture = [...,...]
  loads a list of textures. again, leading whitespace is trimmed
  but trailing until the , or ] is not.
- TEXTURE MAP STATEMENTS
	the texture map is is a corresponding uv coordinate pair for
	each xyz coordinate trio of the points on a triangle
  - texmap = [(x,y),(x,y),(x,y),...]
		binds texture coordinates to triangles in the same order as
		they are in the stl file. this is a pain in the ass to do
		manually :E. number of texmap coords can't exceed number of
		triangles
	- texmap_scale(x,y) and texmap_offset(x,y)
		transforms the texmap, same as the model transformation
		functions. might add texmap_rotate later idk
	- texmap_filldefault(a,b)
		this one's a bit complicated. a and b can be the characters
		x,y, or z and this one sets the texmap coords to their
		corresponding mesh coords (the ones in the stl file)
		according to a and b. so texmap_filldefault(y,z) would set
		each texmap coord's x and y to their mesh coord's y and z,
		respectively. doesn't reassign previously assigned texmap
		coordinate pairs (i'm pretty sure)
	- texmap_filldefault()
		sets texmap coords as if their meshspace triangle were
		flattened to an xy plane, preserving distance. also doesn't
		reassign again i HOPE
- TEXTURE BINDING STATEMENTS
	the texture bindings are which texture each triangle gets.
	it's just an array of indices basically
	- tex_binds = [a,b,...]
		assigns the array. a,b,... are integers less than 256 (you
		can't have more that many textuers per rgmdl) and also less
		than the number of textures you have loaded at the moment.
		it's again in order of the triangles and correspond to
		those. each is by default 0
	- tex_set(a,b)
		sets texture binding at index a to value b
